TY  - JOUR
AU  - Foellmi, Reto
AU  - Zweimüller, Josef
T1  - Income Distribution and Demand-Induced Innovations
PY  - 2006
Y1  - 2006/10/01
DO  - 10.1111/j.1467-937X.2006.00403.x
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 73
IS  - 4
SP  - 941
EP  - 960
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We introduce non-homothetic preferences into an innovation-based growth model and study how income and wealth inequality affect economic growth. We identify a (positive) price effect—where increasing inequality allows innovators to charge higher prices and (negative) market-size effects—with higher inequality implying smaller markets for new goods and/or a slower transition of new goods into mass markets. It turns out that price effects dominate market-size effects. We also show that a redistribution from the poor to the rich may be Pareto improving for low levels of inequality.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-937X.2006.00403.x
ER  - 



